webpackJsonp([85827075196140],{298:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{post:{title:"Edition 18 (4/4/2018)",content:'<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Friends,</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">We hope everybody is having an auspicious start to the week. We&rsquo;re here to make it even better.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">It&rsquo;s already April, and things are heating up outdoors just as they are in the international trade arena. As a side note, co-writer Mark finished college recently (Go Bruins). Congrats are in order, and we&rsquo;re excited for him to pour more of his energies into this brief on a weekly basis. Just kidding. But seriously.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><u>Tech Continues to Lead the Way&hellip;in the Wrong Direction</u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Beginning last week, Tesla ($TSLA) got hammered on both the equity and debt side. Given the litany of negative catalysts that bubbled up for Tesla recently, one might have expected Elon Musk (CEO) to provide serious guidance in response. Instead, he took April fool&rsquo;s day as an opportunity to flippantly&nbsp;<a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/980566116614291456" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">joke</span></a>&nbsp;about bankruptcy.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">We&rsquo;ll let you decide if a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-28/tesla-says-cause-of-fatal-crash-not-yet-known-without-car-s-logs" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">car crashing</span></a>&nbsp;on autopilot,&nbsp;<a href="https://mises.org/library/balance-sheet-normalization-or-not" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">a 100,000+ car re-call</span></a>, a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/27/moodys-downgrades-tesla-credit-rating-on-model-3-production-delays.html" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">credit downgrade</a>, and a drastically souring debt coverage situation are laughing matters. Musk has had the Midas touch in the past, but from our perspective, it&rsquo;s probably time for him to buckle in and address investor concerns head on.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">It&rsquo;s likely clear to you why a car crashing in an unproven autopilot mode and a separate re-call are bad for Tesla. What has really caught the astute investors&rsquo; attention over the last week however has been the action in the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/secondarymarket.asp" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">secondary market</span></a>&nbsp;for Tesla&rsquo;s debt.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Tesla bonds with longer-date maturities (~2025) sold off aggressively last week (see March 23rd&nbsp;to March 29th):</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="color:#14171a"><img alt="https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DZx8IptVwAAnaNo.jpg:large" class="CToWUd a6T" id="m_7180104988917999761Picture_x0020_5" src="https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=998c65c245&amp;view=fimg&amp;th=16291c535df7671e&amp;attid=0.1&amp;disp=emb&amp;attbid=ANGjdJ8uqzSHOCjcCJfmtKZRHbe4ZP7jFgqrtWeO0SMMbM67EbdeuXdsNQVGlnrN4PiVtHFnUqASPF_WEQFPoNujJx5sjq9DomrN81Okye_f-UL4qCihiwZQo45hDEk&amp;sz=w1248-h668&amp;ats=1523332855029&amp;rm=16291c535df7671e&amp;zw&amp;atsh=1" style="cursor:pointer; height:334px; outline:0px; width:624px" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">(<a href="https://twitter.com/lisaabramowicz1/status/980795344807170048" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">chart credit</a>)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">As we have discussed previously, bond prices and bond&nbsp;<a href="https://twitter.com/lisaabramowicz1/status/980793923101712384" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><em><span style="color:blue">yields</span></em></a>&nbsp;are inversely related. Bond yields are the return investors realize on bonds. If demand for &ndash; and thereby price of &ndash; a bond fall, investors require higher returns on those bonds to compensate for additional perceived risk. A rising yield situation can play out as follows:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:1in"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Demand for a corporate bond issue declines, causing price to fall and yields to rise</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:1in"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If the company wishes to issue new bonds to raise capital, it will have a higher cost of debt, as the new, higher yield will dictate what bond payments investors require as their rate of return</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:1in"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If yields rise too high, a company may find that it can&rsquo;t afford to issue new debt</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:1in"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If new debt can&rsquo;t be issued, a company may struggle to make payments on existing debt, and may begin to default on debt payments</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in; margin-right:0in"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">a.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Companies will struggle especially if debt constitutes a large portion of their&nbsp;<a href="https://twitter.com/lisaabramowicz1/status/980793923101712384" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">capital structure</span></a>, if they have significant amounts of debt maturing soon, or if they have low income (often we use&nbsp;<a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/e/ebitda.asp" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">EBITDA</span></a>) relative to their debt obligations</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">One problem for Tesla that exacerbates the above outlined weakness in its bonds is the rate at which it is burning through cash. Tesla is burning through&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-03/musk-needs-to-recharge-tesla-s-finances-to-make-the-model-3-go" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">$6,500&nbsp;<em>per minute</em></a>. That&rsquo;s not a typo. Tesla still operates in a pre-profit business model; they are taking losses now in hopes of developing a robust sales pipeline for the long term. As Tesla eats through its cash, it runs increased risk of defaulting on debt payments as they come due.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Tesla did post some positive news this week, touting &nbsp;strong&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-03/tesla-model-3-output-misses-forecast-as-musk-promises-progress?utm_source=twitter&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=socialflow-organic&amp;cmpid%3D=socialflow-twitter-tictoc&amp;utm_content=tictoc" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">Model S sales</a>&nbsp;for the past quarter. The firm has recovered ground since Monday accordingly, but the above outlined concerns remain paramount.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Also leading the charge on the downside&nbsp;Monday&nbsp;was Amazon, which sold off more than 5% in light of&nbsp;<a href="http://money.cnn.com/2018/04/02/news/companies/amazon-stock-trump/index.html" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">tweets</span></a>&nbsp;from President Trump that touted possible regulatory action. Many on both sides of the political spectrum, including observers as disparate as Trump and Bernie Sanders, think Amazon has become too large and monopolistic, among other points of contention.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><u>Spotify: Disrupting the Music Industry, and the Market Down-Trend?</u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">After several years of rumors, the music streaming service finally made its maiden voyage into the public markets. But it did so in an unconventional manner. Rather than filing for an Initial Public Offering (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Initial_public_offering" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">IPO</a>), in which investment banks help establish company share prices on the public markets, Spotify went public via a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bing.com/search?q=direct+public+offering&amp;filters=ufn%3a%22direct+public+offering%22+sid%3a%220878bde1-0165-efa3-c38c-81d6260487e9%22&amp;FORM=SNAPST" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">direct listing</a>&nbsp;(or direct public offering).</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">How do these styles differ? In an IPO, the filing company retains investment banks to smoothly &ldquo;guide&rdquo; the client by finding initial buyers of the company&rsquo;s shares, stoking demand, and setting a range for the share price. This results in a less volatile opening as shares are available only to institutional investors at first. Eligible investors are selected by the investment banks who underwrite the deal.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Conversely, in its direct listing, Spotify did not issue any new shares; rather, it provided existing investors with a liquidity event that allowed them to cash out if they so desired. Without the guidance of banks, the initial share price in a direct listing is typically more volatile. Spotify (which is valued at ~$20-25B) is the largest company ever to go public this way.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Daniel Elk, Spotify&rsquo;s CEO, noted that &ldquo;the traditional model of taking a company public isn&#39;t a good fit for [Spotify],&rdquo; and has gone on to shun the theatrics of ringing the opening bell at the New York Stock Exchange (an event to which they were invited).</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Elk likely hopes to appeal to the average Joe with his anti-Wall Street rhetoric. Still, the primary motivation for public listing is to provide early private investors with the opportunity for outsized payouts.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Needless to say, the pressure is on Spotify. The company has expanded its top line dramatically over the past four years, but it has incurred greater losses in doing so:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><img class="CToWUd a6T" id="m_7180104988917999761Picture_x0020_4" src="https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=998c65c245&amp;view=fimg&amp;th=16291c535df7671e&amp;attid=0.2&amp;disp=emb&amp;attbid=ANGjdJ-D6od6VxFcNg2Bf42KlFGlqHQa2GUETKjtePyfUnIeac8hAP6xrPNimXWy5Pqi0WLHaeeeybNX8wGoRVLUaKx03avQdZQZgMIcPuci0rDCihiygISqobbvzyo&amp;sz=w696-h636&amp;ats=1523332855030&amp;rm=16291c535df7671e&amp;zw&amp;atsh=1" style="cursor:pointer; height:318px; outline:0px; width:348px" /></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">While its margins have improved recently, the company must soon begin to pivot towards profitability, especially if it wishes to prove successful in the public markets.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">And how did the direct listing go&nbsp;on Tuesday? $SPOT opened up surging. The price lurched from an approximately outlined $132 level quickly into the $160s, representative of a ~ $30B market cap and a 20% premium to opening price.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Shares are trading lower again today, but&nbsp;we&rsquo;ll see how $SPOT performs in the coming days and week. Maybe it can lead the market in a better overall direction than other big tech names.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><u>Trade War Temper Tantrum</u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">While we&rsquo;ve oscillated wildly over trade war fears in recent weeks, it looks like the beginnings of a trade war are now&nbsp;<a href="http://abcnews.go.com/Business/markets-drop-458-points-news-china-tariffs-trade/story?id=54182080" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">on for good</a>, though we&rsquo;re probably still in the posturing phase.&nbsp;On Monday, China announced retaliatory measures in response to previously announced U.S. tariffs on steel and aluminum. China levied new,&nbsp;<em>immediately effective</em>&nbsp;tariffs on U.S.&nbsp;<a href="https://www.msn.com/en-us/video/news/china-raises-tariffs-on-more-than-100-us-goods/vi-AAvo9JG" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">exports</span></a>&nbsp;such as pork and fruit. Similarly, on Wednesday, China announced&nbsp;<a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-stocks/boeing-ford-lead-list-of-casualties-in-china-u-s-trade-spat-idUSKCN1HB1FM" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">further tit-for tat</a>&nbsp;tariffs on a longer list of U.S. goods, though the effective date of these new tariffs is yet undetermined.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Pork and soybeans are especially important U.S. exports to China. Over the past decade, the Chinese economic boom has resulted in robust middle class growth. This middle class has a voracious appetite for pork. Though we often think of jobs in America being outsourced to China, China actually outsourced a lot of their pork production to the U.S. They didn&rsquo;t want to deal with all the pig shit,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/why-is-china-treating-north-carolina-like-the-developing-world-w517973" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">literally</span></a>.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Meanwhile, the U.S. exports&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-04/brewing-trade-spat-takes-aim-at-u-s-swing-state-soybeans-map?utm_content=business&amp;utm_source=twitter&amp;utm_campaign=socialflow-organic&amp;cmpid=socialflow-twitter-business&amp;utm_medium=social" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">more soybeans&nbsp;</a>than any other agricultural product.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="color:#0e67b0"><img alt="Bar graph showing the top U.S. agricultural exports in 2017.  Soybeans was the highest at $21.6 billion, followed by corn and tree nuts. " class="CToWUd a6T" id="m_7180104988917999761Picture_x0020_3" src="https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=998c65c245&amp;view=fimg&amp;th=16291c535df7671e&amp;attid=0.3&amp;disp=emb&amp;attbid=ANGjdJ9opfThLZ6Fqj6Yhx2E6Vi5mrESRtFt0-ZNiU8x-lGG6R2stThhm-bRKed07nVvyUOGOsdCaqakqNNj5K413ou5hkJbpd6XaU_P3vNe4-wxMn33poMi4gT2E24&amp;sz=w972-h862&amp;ats=1523332855031&amp;rm=16291c535df7671e&amp;zw&amp;atsh=1" style="cursor:pointer; height:431px; outline:0px; width:486px" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">The&nbsp;<em>immediately</em>&nbsp;effective&nbsp;<a href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2018/04/02/china-raises-tariffs-us-products/477428002/" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">25%</span></a>&nbsp;tariff threatens pork exports most directly.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">With respect to China:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0.5in; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><a href="https://www.mercurynews.com/2018/04/01/china-sets-tariffs-on-128-us-exports-including-pork-and-fruit/" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">&ldquo;The National Pork Producers Council said in late March that its members exported $1.1 billion in pork to China last year, making it the third-largest market.&rdquo;</a></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Per these figures, China alone accounts for 15-20% of US pork exports.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Commodity traders took the news quite seriously&nbsp;on Monday. This was best illustrated in Lean Hogs futures trading. Lean Hog futures are standardized contracts that specify buyers and sellers for pre-defined amounts of pork at future dates. Declines in prices for lean hog futures indicate lower expected future demand.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Hog futures&nbsp;<a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-markets-cme-hogs/china-tariff-hike-on-u-s-pork-sinks-cme-hogs-to-16-month-low-idUSKCN1H91MH" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">have lost 28%</span></a>&nbsp;of their value since February 5th, as trade war fears have picked up in earnest. The below shows the performance of the&nbsp;May 18&nbsp;Lean Hog futures contract as tariffs on pork were announced:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><img alt="http://data.tradingcharts.com/intraday_charts/charts_fe/1e94d5ed9caf674cd7008b1b57472502.png?25378206" class="CToWUd a6T" id="m_7180104988917999761Picture_x0020_2" src="https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=998c65c245&amp;view=fimg&amp;th=16291c535df7671e&amp;attid=0.4&amp;disp=emb&amp;attbid=ANGjdJ9Ku3hLZf9Nfawy6304JxcMXQsTyQgQXQkkZpM6E-rMZB0L5qfCsEQ6O1n3YZQu3ub6Vz-2E4ZmikgpWUdr2WJgzPuhj8dH603TszejukMxkBWzVBKLxzkX4b8&amp;sz=w1054-h766&amp;ats=1523332855032&amp;rm=16291c535df7671e&amp;zw&amp;atsh=1" style="cursor:pointer; height:383px; outline:0px; width:527px" /></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Similarly, Tyson Foods, one of the world&rsquo;s largest meat producers ($TSN), was down over&nbsp;<a href="https://seekingalpha.com/news/3342954-tariff-concerns-hit-tyson-foods" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">6%&nbsp;Monday</span></a>.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">To round out our commodity analysis, a major Soybean tracking ETF ($SOYB) was on track to lost over&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bing.com/search?q=%24soyb&amp;form=EDGEAR&amp;qs=PF&amp;cvid=751b72de929b4fc8a6cd62d6b7996c20&amp;cc=US&amp;setlang=en-US" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank">3% Wednesday</a>.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><u>Support No More</u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Remember when we discussed the 200 day moving average (200 MA) just last week, and how it had held as support for the S&amp;P 500 futures twice this year? The levee has been breached. The vicious selling that opened the week, spurred by the catalysts we have discussed at length now,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-01/asian-stocks-set-for-muted-start-to-second-quarter-markets-wrap" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">busted through the 200 MA to the downside</span></a>. This is the first instance of a break below the 200 MA since overnight futures trading after the U.S. presidential election.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">The below chart illustrates the breach of the 200 MA (the turquoise line) in the S&amp;P 500:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff"><span style="color:#14171a"><img alt="https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DZyerBmWkAQmArv.jpg:large" class="CToWUd a6T" id="m_7180104988917999761Picture_x0020_1" src="https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=998c65c245&amp;view=fimg&amp;th=16291c535df7671e&amp;attid=0.5&amp;disp=emb&amp;attbid=ANGjdJ-qzub9U9CzuXHVMbbGA8WQir4T87Hz2DPjbxV0maDURZ9SyBI_u_TVb8aHXI3Q2VhaU8Jc9t3-EvIrJFqr37qjnCU6g1Zof_WJ2-hVS-pXpP89Hxfm0h4DSQo&amp;sz=w1248-h744&amp;ats=1523332855032&amp;rm=16291c535df7671e&amp;zw&amp;atsh=1" style="cursor:pointer; height:372px; outline:0px; width:624px" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">(<a href="https://twitter.com/StockTwits/status/980833337525854210" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">chart credit</span></a>)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Next up? The&nbsp;<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-01/asian-stocks-set-for-muted-start-to-second-quarter-markets-wrap" style="color:#1155cc" target="_blank"><span style="color:blue">lows from February</span></a>&nbsp;are another watermark markets could re-test. Keep an eye on this 200 MA level, as its frequent recurrence seems to beget its importance.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Markets have recovered incrementally since Monday, and there&rsquo;s flirtation with green at the time of this delivery, despite the new Chinese tariff announcements. These are tough markets to navigate, as volatility remains well above short-run averages for the past years of the bull market.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">We&rsquo;ll stay at the helm for you.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in"><span style="color:#222222"><span style="background-color:#ffffff">Nick + Mark</span></span></p>',updated:"2018-04-10T04:03:12.891528Z",fields:{slug:"Edition-18",date:"(4/4/2018)"}}},pathContext:{slug:"Edition-18"}}}});
